Hi

>> Do you think wrapping enums/flags as objects has advantages? PyGtk 2.3.x
>> seems to do it this way.
> backtracking, a class/function could be made which could be called when 
> the programmer needs the name explicitly. The function returns the name 
> b) one function which accepts a "enum type group" as parameter
>    getEnumName( 4, ENUM_CURSOR);

I just sat down and made such a function, but see yourself:

8<=================

<?php
/**
*   helper function to determine return values
*   @author Christian Weiske <cweiske@php.net>
*/

//that we have something to find
if( !extension_loaded('gtk')) {
     dl( 'php_gtk.' . PHP_SHLIB_SUFFIX);
}


/**
*   returns a enum name for a given value
*   you can (and should) specify a group like "PLOT" or so
*   to limit the search results
*/
function resolvEnum( $nValue, $strGroup = '')
{
     $strGroup = strtoupper( $strGroup);

     $arEnums    = get_defined_constants();
     $arFound    = array();

     foreach( $arEnums as $strEnumName => $nDefValue)
     {
         if( $nValue !== $nDefValue) continue;
         //here we could remove all the not GTK_ and GDK_ constants if 
we'd like to

         if( strstr( $strEnumName, '_' . $strGroup . '_') === false
             && substr( $strEnumName, 0,  strlen( $strGroup) + 1) !== 
$strGroup . '_'
         ) {
             continue;
         }
         $arFound[]  = $strEnumName;
     }
     return $arFound;
}//function resolvEnum( $nValue, $strGroup = '')

var_dump( resolvEnum( 4, 'PLOT'));
var_dump( resolvEnum( 4, 'PLO'));
var_dump( resolvEnum( 3, 'GDK_WINDOW'));
?>

8<=================


